<DOC><DOCNO> AP890715-0044 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-89 0833EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Typhoon 1stLd-Writethru   07-15 0309</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Philippines-Typhoon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0470,0318</SECOND><HEAD>Typhoon Roars Toward Philippines, U.S. Bases on Alert</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after 5th graf `Strong winds...' to UPDATE withdetails on alert at Clark Air Base. Pickup 6th graf `Gordon is...'</HEAD><DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Typhoon Gordon, the strongest storm tothreaten the Philippines this year, gained strength today as itroared toward Luzon, the country's main island, officials said.   Storm warnings were raised over 10 provinces and at the six U.S.military bases. The U.S. military's Far East Network describedGordon as a ``super typhoon'' and said it would strike the northernisland of Luzon early Sunday.   At 5 p.m., Gordon had peak winds of 128 mph and was headingtoward Luzon at 14 mph from a position 270 miles northeast of Manila.   Earlier today, Gordon had top winds of 116 mph.   Strong winds buffeted Manila late today, but there were noreports of damage.   At Clark Air Base, 50 miles north of Manila, officials canceledall inspections, training and other activities. The U.S.-run base'semergency rescue and clean-up units were placed on alert andnon-essential personnel were ordered home.   The Far East Network said some Military Airlift Command flightsto and from Clark would also be canceled because of the typhoon.Heavy rains were expected in the Clark area late today, officialssaid.   There are 40,000 U.S. troops, civilian employees and militarydependents stationed at the six installations.   Gordon is expected to cut across the northern tip of Luzon beforeit moves out to the South China Sea later Sunday, weatherforecasters said.   Residents of coastal areas were warned to take ``extremeprecaution'' against high waves and flash floods.   The Philippine Coast Guard ordered all sea-going vessels on Luzonnot to leave port.   Philippine Airlines said it canceled one domestic flight andexpected to ground more planes as the typhoon neared.</TEXT></DOC>